Motivation for Flexible Statistical Modeling

Econometrics Vs Machine Learning

  • Econometrics:
    • building traditional statistical methods to estimate economic relationships & testing economic theories (Greene, 2011)

  • Machine Learning:
    • a set of methods that can automatically learn models of data (Murphy, 2013; Ghahramani, 2014)

# Econometrics Machine Learning
1. Define hypothesis, test it Define generative model, learn parameters
2. Focuses on apriori hypotheses Evaluates results via prediction accuracy
3. Emphasize super population inference Emphasize prediction
4. Simpler models preferred Concern for overfitting, not model complexity
5. Emphasis on interpretable models Emphasis on performance
6. Build model once & deploy Model continously improves
7. Human improvement Automated improvement after deployment
8. Standard models e.g Poisson Also uses Blackbox models e.g neural nets

Overview of Parametric Regression

  • Parametric Modeling
    • Models with a finite set of parameters (e.g. mean, variance) to capture entire complexity in observed data

    \[P(\textbf{y}\mid\textbf{x}) = \mathcal{N}(\textbf{y}\mid\mu, \sigma^{2}) \]

    \[\mu = \mathbb{E}[\textbf{y}\mid\textbf{x}, \beta] = \beta_0 + \beta\textbf{x} \]

Challenges of Parametric Regression

  1. How do we pick the form of functions to use as our model?

  1. How do we represent the uncertainty in our model due to?
    • Noisy data,
    • Poor model, etc.

Parametric Bayesian Modeling (1/2)

  • Bayesian Modeling:
    • The process of fitting a probability model to data & summarizing the result using a probability distribution (Gelman, 2014)

Parametric Bayesian Modeling (2/2)

  • Allows to incorporate domain knowledge & quantify uncertainty

Nonparametric Bayesian Modeling (1/4)

  • Recall Bayes theorem for the parametric case:
    • \(\theta\) are the unknown parameters we seek to learn e.g \(\{\beta, \sigma \}\)

\[ P(\theta \mid y,x) = \frac{P(y \mid \theta,x) \, P(\theta)}{P(y\midx)} \]

  • In the Nonparametric case:
    • Instead, We want to learn the function \(f\) that explains the data:

    \[y=f(x)+\varepsilon\]

    • \(f\) is now treated as the unknown parameter we seek to learn


  • Now modify the above Bayes theorem to non-parametric:
    • By placing prior over an \(\infty\)-dimensional space of functions, \(p(f)\)

\[ P(f\mid y,x) = \frac{P(y \mid f) \, P(f \mid x)}{P(y \mid x)} \]

Nonparametric Bayesian Modeling (2/4)

  • What is this prior distribution over functions, \(p(f)\)?
    • It’s the infinite set of imaginable functions
    • It’s called a Gaussian Process (GP) prior

Nonparametric Bayesian Modeling (3/4)

  • a GP prior is parameterized by: \[f(x) \sim GP(m(x), k(x, x'))\]
    • \(m(x)\) = mean function
    • \(k(x, x')\) = covariance (kernel) function

  • Any finite set of function evaluations \(f(x_i)_1^N\) have a joint Gaussian distribution (Williams and Rasmussen 2006).

Nonparametric Bayesian Modeling (4/4)

  • The updated Bayes formula for the GP posterior: \[ P(f\mid y,x) = \frac{P(y \mid f) \, P(f \mid x)}{P(y \mid x)} = \frac{P(y \mid f) \, \mathcal{N}(m(x), K(x))}{P(y \mid x)} \]

  • A fitted GP posterior on the same data looks like:
    • Shows both mean & covariance functions
    • Areas without data have high uncertainity & vice versa

Modeling High Dimensional Problems

  • High number of variables increases computational requirements
  • Proposed solution
    • Decompose the high-dimensional function \(f_D\) into a sum of \(N\) low-dimensional functions

\[f_D(x_1, x_2, ..., x_D)=f_1(x_1, x_2) + f_2(x_3) + ... + f_N(x_D)\]

Example
Parametric Vs Nonparametric

Bayesian Linear Model (1/4)

  • Objective: predict mpg as a function of displacement (disp). \[\begin{aligned} y &= f(\textbf{x}) + \varepsilon, \\ f(\textbf{x}) &= \beta_0 + \beta\textbf{x}. \end{aligned}\]
    • Assume additive noise
    • Assume \(\varepsilon \stackrel{\text{iid}}{\sim} \mathcal{N}(0, \sigma^2)\)

Bayesian Linear Model (2/4)

  • Step 1: Define priors on the parameters, \(\theta\)
    • Intercept: \(\beta_0 \sim \mathcal{N}(0, 20)\)
    • Slope: \(\beta_1 \sim \mathcal{N}(0, 15)\)
    • Noise-deviation: \(\sigma \sim \mathcal{N}(0, 5)\)

Bayesian Linear Model (3/4)

  • Step 2: Define the likelihood \[ \begin{aligned} P(\textbf{y}\mid\textbf{x}, \mathbf{\theta}) & = \mathcal{N}(\mu, \sigma^{2}) = \mathcal{N}(\beta_0 + \beta\textbf{x}, \sigma^{2}) \end{aligned} \]

  • Step 3: Find the posterior of parameters \[ \begin{aligned} P(\theta \mid \textbf{y}, \textbf{x}) &\propto P(\theta ) P(\textbf{y} \mid \textbf{x}, \mathbf{\theta}) \end{aligned} \]

Bayesian Linear Model (4/4)

  • Step 4: Validate the model on test data, \(\textbf{x}_*\)

\[ \begin{aligned} P(\textbf{y}_* \mid \textbf{x}_*, \textbf{x, y}) = \int P(\theta \mid \textbf{y}, \textbf{x}) P(\textbf{y}_*\mid\textbf{x}_*, \theta) \, d\theta \end{aligned} \]

Bayesian Nonparametric Model (1/5)

  • Recall: the Bayesian nonparametric model, Gaussian process prior.
    \[f(x) \sim GP(m(x), k(x, x'))\]
    • \(m(x)\) = mean function
    • \(k(x, x')\) = covariance function (kernel)


  • The standard kernel is the Squared Exponential (SE) kernel, \(k_y\), below: \[k_y(x_i, x_j\mid\theta) = \sigma^2_fexp\bigg(-\frac{1}{2l^2}(x_i-x_j)^2\bigg) + \delta_{ij}\sigma^2_n\]
    • \(\sigma^2_f\) = signal-variance parameter
    • \(l\) = length-scale parameter (\(l\) is positive; controls smoothness)
    • \(\delta_{ij}\) = Kronecker delta function (\(\delta_{ij}\) = 1 iff \(i = j\) and 0 otherwise)
    • \(\sigma^2_n\) = noise-variance parameter

Bayesian Nonparametric Model (2/5)

  • Step 1: Define a prior, \(p(f)\) on the parameter, \(f\):
    • signal-variance: \(\sigma_f \sim \mathcal{N}(0, 1)\)
    • length-scale: \(l \sim \mathcal{Gamma}(150, 1)\)
    • noise-variance: \(\sigma_n \sim \mathcal{N}(1, 0.1)\)
    • prior-functions: \(\textbf{y} \sim \mathcal{MultiNormal}(0, k_{\sigma^2_f,l}(x_i, x_j)+\sigma^2_n\textit{I}_n)\)

Bayesian Nonparametric Model (3/5)

Bayesian Nonparametric Model (4/5)

  • Step 2: Define the likelihood \[ \begin{aligned} P(y \mid f, \sigma_n) = \mathcal{N}(y \mid f, \sigma^{2}_n) \end{aligned} \]

  • Step 3: Find the posterior of the function: \[ \begin{aligned} P(f\mid y,x) & \propto P(y \mid f, \sigma_n) \, P(f \mid x) \\ & \propto \mathcal{N}(y \mid f, \sigma^{2}_n) \, \mathcal{N}(m(x), k_y(x_i, x_j\mid\theta)) \end{aligned} \]

Bayesian Nonparametric Model (5/5)

  • Step 4: Validate the model on test data \[ P(\textbf{y}_*\mid\textbf{x}_*, \textbf{x, y}) = \int P(\textbf{f} \mid y,x) \, P(\textbf{y}_*\mid\textbf{x}_*, \textbf{f}) \, d\textbf{f} \]

Task I
Estimation of Integrated and Highly Dimensional Travel Demand Models

The Research Problem

  • Transport planners often desire to learn from raw data insightful travel patterns such as:
    • periodic variations,
    • distinct behavioral clusters,
    • market segments, etc.

  • To extract these hidden insights, probabilistic models are developed.
    • Models attempt to explain the observed data.

  • Assumptions have to be made,, such as:
    • The data were generated by an underlying latent process with some set of parameters that can be inferred from the data

Related Work and Limitations (1/2)

  • How do we pick the form of functions to use as our model?

McHutchon (2016)

  • How do we represent the uncertainty in our model due to?
    • Noisy data,
    • Noisy model, etc.

Related Work and Limitations (2/2)

  • Campbell et al. (2016) proposed a Hidden Markov Model (HMM) to capture activity states.

  • The main limitation:
    • It does not completely capture temporal variability in activities,
    • HMMs consider activity states to have constant durations.

Proposed Solution

  • Activity-based human mobility is made up of both high-level and low-level states.

Emaasit et al. (2017)

Expected Contribution from Task I

  • A flexible statistical method to estimate high dimensional travel demand choice problems.
    • No need to pre-specify complex functional form,
    • Easy to interprete,
    • Easy to extend,
    • Cheap to compute.

Task II
Capturing Latent Travel Patterns with Unknown Number of Activities

The Research Problem (1/2)

The Research Problem (2/2)

  • There’s a crucial need for effective methods to infer mobility patterns using CDR data.

  • These methods must address several challenges:
    • spatially sparse CDR data,
    • various types of uncertainty,
    • lack of ground truth,
    • complexity due to the size of the data,
    • diversity of phone users, e.t.c


  • The modeling process needs to provide superior or similar results as currently available Activity-Based Models (ABM).
    • ABM are the current state-of-the-art for transportation planning.

Related Work and Limitations

  • Irregular but highly ordered events that happen less often, with strong dependencies, are not considered
    • Models that capture frequent visits are biased to stay/anchor locations.

CDR data in South Africa

Proposed Solution

  • Activity-based mobility of human travel is made up of travel events that are less frequent but significantly influence travel demand.

A model for rare events

Expected Contributions from Task II

  • A method to estimate cardinality of hidden underlying processes.

  • A method to identify transitions from one stable regime to another.

Task III
Automating Travel Demand Model Selection and Parameter Tuning

The Research Problem (1/2)

Attributes of CDR data

Attributes of household surveys

The Research Problem (2/2)

  • There’s a crucial need for effective methods to infer mobility patterns using CDR data.

  • These methods must address several challenges:
    • spatially sparse CDR data,
    • various types of uncertainty,
    • lack of ground truth,
    • complexity due to the size of the data,
    • diversity of phone users, e.t.c


  • The modeling process needs to provide superior or similar results as currently available Activity-Based Models (ABM).
    • ABM are the current state-of-the-art for transportation planning.

Related Work and Limitations

  • Low granular sub-states in activity sequences are not considered.

Typical mobility patterns with high-level and low-level states

  • The main limitation:
    • HMM consider a series of travel behaviors (states) as one-super state,
    • Only higher level states are found i.e. very high granular view of the movement pattern,
    • Sometimes a complete day is discovered as a single state.

Proposed Solution

  • Activity-based mobility states of human travel have varying durations.

A model for temporal variability

Expected Contribution from Task III

  • A method to automate Travel Demand Modeling.

Overall Conclusions

Overall Expected Contributions

  • A method for high dimensional problems (from Task I)

  • A method for addressing cardinality of latent states (from Task II)

  • A method for automating TDM (from Task III)
